knowledge_graph.title: Lemongrass
knowledge_graph.description: Cymbopogon, also known as lemongrass, barbed wire grass, silky heads, oily heads, Cochin grass, Malabar grass, citronella grass or fever grass, is a genus of Asian, African, Australian, and tropical island plants in the grass family.

related_questions.question: Does lemongrass come back every year?
related_questions.snippet: Lemongrass is a tender perennial meaning that it does come back every year so long as you take care of it properly. Lemongrass will die if it is exposed to cold weather and frost so while it can live outside all year round in USDA zones 8b and 9, it will need to be taken indoors in other zones.
related_questions.title: How to grow lemongrass: an easy step-by-step | Homes & Gardens

related_questions.question: What is lemongrass good for?
related_questions.snippet: Now grown in Africa, Australia, and North and South America, lemongrass is widely used as a natural remedy for digestive issues, neurological problems, and high blood pressure. Lemongrass reportedly has antibacterial and antifungal properties. It has traditionally been used as a pain reliever and fever reducer.
related_questions.title: Lemongrass: Are There Health Benefits? - WebMD

related_questions.question: Where is the best place to plant lemongrass?
related_questions.snippet: Lemongrass prefers a full sun spot, but will also tolerate an area that only receives sun for half the day. During warmer, drier weather lemongrass will need regular watering. Apply an open organic mulch around the plants to retain moisture and suppress weeds.
related_questions.title: full sun spot

related_questions.question: Is lemongrass a mosquito repellent?
related_questions.snippet: In any case, citronella and lemongrass are used extensively as a natural mosquito repellent. Both of them contain the compound citronella that helps to mask the scents that mosquitoes rely on to target hosts which is carbon dioxide and lactic acid.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Lemongrass Oil Best For?
buttons.title: Potential Uses of Lemongrass Oil - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Lemongrass is used as a folk remedy for a number of digestive problems, ranging from stomachaches to gastric ulcers. According to a 2018 study on mice, lemongrass essential oil may aid in gastric healing. Lemongrass is also a common ingredient in herbal teas and supplements for nausea.
snippet_highlighted_words: used as a folk remedy for a number of digestive problems, ranging from stomachaches to gastric ulcers

buttons.subtitle: What Does Lemongrass Taste Like
buttons.title: Flavor Focus: Lemongrass
buttons.snippet: Lemongrass is said to taste like mild citrus with a hint of ginger. Named so for its lemony aroma, this herb actually possesses the same oils as the lemon fruit and is often used as a substitute for lemon flavoring. Fresh lemongrass may also offer notes of bright floral and cooling mint.
snippet_highlighted_words: mild citrus with a hint of ginger

buttons.subtitle: How To Plant Lemongrass
buttons.title: Growing & Planting Lemongrass | General Planting & Growing Tips
buttons.snippet: Plant lemongrass in spring, once all chances of frost have passed. It's a perfect plant for growing in-ground, as you would with ornamental grasses, or in containers. Lemongrass likes it hot, so grow it in an area with full sun and fertile, well-drained soil with a pH of 6.5 to 7.0. Space plants 24 inches apart.
snippet_highlighted_words: Plant lemongrass in spring, once all chances of frost have passed
